  <subfield code="m">\Xi \left(\tau \right) must be symmetric, \Xi \left(\tau \right)= \Xi \left(-\tau \right). Time symmetry and general covariance dictate that \Xi \left(\tau \right) must be either symmetric or antisymmetric. However, Parseval&apos;s theorem requires that \Xi \left(\tau \right) must have a nonzero value at zero lag if there is to be any measurable fluctuation in a real-valued signal, eliminating the latter choice</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">The correlation function must respect the causal region in the emergent space. For a simple configuration of two co-aligned Michelson interferometers with characteristic scale L (e.g. arm length), we expect the functional support to be limited by the causal diamond to the interval \tau =\left(-L,+L\right) between reflections at the reference world line (e.g. the beamsplitter), or the interval \tau =\left(-2L,+2L\right) of events that influence the signal at any given time (see figure, 3: #cqgaa601ef03). More general interferometer configurations may add additional scales, or even additional world-lines, and yield different functions</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">3</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">The hypothesis being tested is that relative positions of massive bodies as encoded in \Xi \left(\tau \right) are subject to Planck scale spreading of information just described. For shear modes (but not rotation), scaling symmetry then requires that where it does not vanish, \Xi \left(\tau \right) is linear in Ï„, with a derivative \text{d} \Xi /\text{d}\tau that does not depend on the size of the apparatus (see nested causal diamond in figure, 4: #cqgaa601ef04), but only its shape. To match holographic information content, its absolute value is approximately the Planck time tP. A more careful evaluation of numerical factors follows below</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
